'''Barry Latzer''' (born 1945) is an American criminologist and emeritus professor of [[criminal justice]] at the [[John Jay College of Criminal Justice]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://johnjay.jjay.cuny.edu/newsroom/7843.php |title=Professor Barry Latzer’s Op-ed on the Shooting in Ferguson, MO Published in the New York Post |website=John Jay College of Criminal Justice}}</ref> He previously taught at the [[Graduate Center, CUNY]]. He also prosecuted and defended accused criminals while teaching both there and at John Jay.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/the-cultural-roots-of-crime/487583/ |title=The Cultural Roots of Crime |last=Frum |first=David |authorlink=David Frum |website=The Atlantic |publication-date=19 June 2016}}</ref> In 2016, his book ''The Rise and Fall of Violent Crime in America'' was published by [[Encounter Books]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-american-interest.com/2016/02/23/backlash/ |title=Backlash |last=Willick |first=Jason |website=The American Interest |publication-date=23 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/9/1/11805346/violent-crime-america-barry-latzer-book-review |title=Confronting the myth that “black culture” is responsible for violent crime in America |last=Lopez |first=Graham |website=Vox |publication-date=1 September 2016}}</ref> He is an expert on [[core curricula]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/05/AR2005090501119.html |title=Freshman Classes Getting Hooked on the Classics |last=Mathews |first=Jay |website=The Washington Post |publication-date=6 September 2005}}</ref> and a supporter [[capital punishment]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2002/02/11/death.htm |title=Fight against death penalty gains ground |last=Willing |first=Richard |website=USA Today |publication-date=11 February 2002}}</ref> ==Education== Latzer received his Ph.D. in [[political science]] from the [[University of Massachusetts, Amherst]] in 1977, and his J.D. from [[Fordham University]] in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/books/death-penalty-cases/latzer/978-0-12-382024-2 |title=Death Penalty Cases |website=Elsevier}}</ref> ==Books== *''State Constitutions and Criminal Justice'' ([[Greenwood Press]], 1991) *''State Constitutional Criminal Law'' ([[West (publisher)|Clark, Boardman, Callaghan]], 1995) *''Death Penalty Cases'' ([[Butterworth-Heinemann]], 2002) *''The Rise and Fall of Violent Crime in America'' (Encounter Books, 2016)
