{{one source|date=April 2016}} '''Canadian Impressionism''' is a subclass of [[Impressionism|Impressionist]] art influenced from French Impressionism. [[Guy Wildenstein]] of the [[Wildenstein Institute]] in Paris states in the foreword of A.K. Prakash's ''Impressionism in Canada: A Journey of Rediscovery'' that Canadian impressionism is "the Canadian artists who gleaned much from the French but, in their improvisations, managed to transmute what they learned into an art reflecting the aesthetic concerns of their compatriots and the times in which they lived and worked".<ref>Prakash. 2015. p. xxv</ref> The early Canadian Impressionist painters belong into the "Group of who?" as coined by James Adams of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/group-of-who-a-new-book-paints-the-fullest-picture-yet-of-canadas-vision-of-impressionism/article21967828/|title=Group of who? A new book paints the fullest picture yet of Canada's vision of Impressionism|last=Adams|first=James|date=December 5, 2014|website=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Globe and Mail Inc.|access-date=}}</ref>
== History == Canada's first affair with Impressionism occurred in 1892 in Montreal at W. Scott & Sons' premises. Eight paintings were exhibited including works of [[Monet]], [[Renoir]], [[Camille Pissarro|Pissarro]] and [[Alfred Sisley|Sisley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/arts/visual-arts-montreal-played-key-role-in-spread-of-impressionism-to-canada|title=Visual arts: Montreal played key role in spread of Impressionism to Canada|last=Pohl|first=John|date=February 5, 2015|website=Montreal Gazette|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|access-date=}}</ref> Canadian Impressionism was first recognized as a historical movement in ''[[Canadian Art (magazine)|Canadian Art]]'' in 1950.<ref>Prakash. 2015. p. 11</ref>
== Artists == * [[William Blair Bruce]]<ref name=as>{{cite web|title=Visions of Light and Air: Canadian Impressionism, 1885-1920|url=http://www.as-coa.org/exhibitions/visions-light-and-air-canadian-impressionism-1885-1920|website=Americas Society / Council of the Americas|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref> * [[Ernest Lawson]]<ref name=as/> * [[William Henry Clapp]]<ref name=as/>
== List of notable Canadian Impressionist collectors == Prakash acknowledges in his book a few notable collectors of Canadian Impressionist art.<ref>Prakash. 2015. p. 34</ref>
