{{EngvarB|date=December 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Rohingya people in Pakistan | image = | caption = | population = {{circa|200,000}}<ref name="MahmudTohid"/><ref name="Sajjad"/> | popplace = [[Karachi]] | langs = [[Rohingya language|Rohingya]]{{·}}[[Burmese language|Burmese]]{{·}}[[Chittagonian language|Chittagonian]]{{·}}[[Urdu]]{{·}}[[English language|English]] and [[Languages of Burma|other Myanmar languages]] | rels = [[Islam]]{{·}}[[Hinduism]] | related = [[:Category:Burmese diaspora|Burmese diaspora]] }}
'''Rohingya people in Pakistan''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|پاکستانی برمی}}}}) are a community based in [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]]. They are [[Rohingya]] [[Muslim]]s ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|روہنگیا مسلمان}}}}) from [[Rakhine State]], [[Myanmar]] (also known as Arakan, Burma), who have fled their homeland because of the [[Persecution of Muslims in Myanmar|persecution of Muslims]] by the Burmese government and [[Buddhist]] majority.<ref>{{cite news|last=Flood|first1=Derek Henry|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/derek-henry-flood/from-south-to-south-refug_b_100387.html|title=From South to South: Refugees as Migrants: The Rohingya in Pakistan|work=The Huffington Post|date=12 May 2008|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> According to varied Pakistani government sources and the Arakan Historical Society, there are some 200,000 Rohingya refugees residing in Pakistan.<ref name="MahmudTohid">{{cite news|last1=Mahmud|first1=Arshad|author2=Owais Tohid|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?200305|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012052259/http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?200305|deadurl=no|archivedate=12 October 2013|title=Homeless in Karachi|magazine=Outlook India|date=29 November 1995|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="Sajjad">{{cite web|last=Sajjad|first=Tazreena|url=http://www.burmalibrary.org/docs/SRI-rohingya.htm|title=SRI On-Site Action Alert: Rohingya Refugees of Burma and UNHCR's repatriation program|publisher=burmalibrary.org|date=17 July 2003|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/322325/five-million-illegal-immigrants-residing-in-pakistan/|title=Five million illegal immigrants residing in Pakistan|newspaper=tribune.com.pk|date=16 January 2012|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> All of them have made a perilous journey across [[Bangladesh]] and [[India]] and have settled in [[Karachi]]. The [[Rohingya]] [[Muslim]] in Karachi have now obtained Pakistani citizenship. A report on human trafficking stated that Burmese people make up fourteen percent of Karachi's undocumented immigrants.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Donna M.|last1=Hughes|authorlink1=Donna M. Hughes|author2=Laura Joy Sporcic|author3=Nadine Z. Mendelsohn|author4=Vanessa Chirgwin|url=http://www.uri.edu/artsci/wms/hughes/pakistan.htm|title=Factbook on Global Sexual Exploitation: Pakistan: Trafficking|publisher=University of Rhode Island, Coalition Against Trafficking in Women|date=1999|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523093644/http://www.uri.edu/artsci/wms/hughes/pakistan.htm|archivedate=23 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Large scale [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]] migration to Karachi made [[Karachi]] one of the largest population centres of [[Rohingya people|Rohingyas]] in the world after Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1165299|title=Identity issue haunts Karachi's Rohingya population|last=Rehman|first=Zia Ur|work=Dawn|date=23 February 2015|access-date=26 December 2016|quote=Their large-scale migration had made Karachi one of the largest Rohingya population centres outside Myanmar but afterwards the situation started turning against them.}}</ref> In the recent years, scores of Burmese women seeking employment have entered the country. Different resources cite the number of these women to be in the thousands.<ref>{{cite web|last=Latif|first=Aamir|url=https://archive.islamonline.net/?p=921|title=Immigrant Dream Shattered in Karachi|publisher=Islam Online|date=24 June 2007|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>
== Rohingyas and Bengalis in Karachi == According to community leaders and social scientists, there are over 1.6 million Bengalis and up to 400,000 Rohingyas living in Karachi.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rehman|first=Zia Ur|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-4-333213-Bengali-and-Rohingya-leaders-gearing-up-for-LG-polls|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814203153/http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-4-333213-Bengali-and-Rohingya-leaders-gearing-up-for-LG-polls|archivedate=14 August 2015|title=Bengali and Rohingya leaders gearing up for LG polls|location=Karachi|newspaper=thenews.com.pk|date=9 August 2015|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> There are numerous Burmese housing colonies that can be found throughout Karachi. Traditionally, cultural similarities of the Rohingya people to those of [[Bengali people|Bengalis]] has enabled easier communication and interaction of the Burmese in Karachi with the [[Bangladeshis in Pakistan|Bengali community]]. Their native [[Rohingya language]] furthermore has dialect familiarities especially with the Bangladeshi natives hailing from [[Chittagong]], who speak a somewhat indistinct [[Chittagonian language]]. As a result of the great inter-ethnic engagement, the Burmese people in Pakistan have a special reputation for being found in areas only that traditionally also contain a Bengali population. With more stringent control and difficulty in traversing borders the Burmese have now started travelling east to countries closer to Burma such as Thailand, Cambodia, Bangladesh, Vietnam and Malaysia. The number of Burmese in Pakistan has been on the decline in recent years.
==Notable people== * [[Eric G. Hall]] - Pakistan Air Force fighter pilot of [[Anglo-Burmese people|Anglo-Burmese]] origin. * [[Ashraf Tai]] - Pioneer of Bando Karate in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saleem |first=Samia |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/204014/you-wouldnt-want-to-pick-a-fight-with-grand-master-ashraf-tais-family/ |title=You wouldn't want to pick a fight with 'Grand Master' Ashraf Tai's family |newspaper=Tribune.com.pk |date=7 July 2011 |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> * [[Rakshanda Khattak]] - fashion model and actress
