{{Historical populations |title = Slovaks citizens in the Czech Republic as of December 31 |source = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.czso.cz/csu/2013edicniplan.nsf/engt/2E003D965E/$File/141413_t1-01.pdf|title=Obsah nenalezen - ČSÚ|website=www.czso.cz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.czso.cz/csu/2014edicniplan.nsf/engt/9A003F3BED/$File/29002714.pdf|title=Obsah nenalezen - ČSÚ|website=www.czso.cz}}</ref> |2011|81253 |2012|85807 |2013|90948 }}
'''Slovaks in the Czech Republic''' are the country's second-largest ethnic minority; after the [[Moravians (ethnic group)|Moravians]], who are native to the [[Czech Republic]]. The American [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] puts them at 1.9% of the country's total population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ez.html|title=The World Factbook — Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref> Larger numbers of them can be found in the country's east, especially [[Ostrava]] and [[Brno]]; as the Czech Republic shares a border in the east with [[Slovakia]].
== Notable people == * [[Andrej Babiš]], Czech politician and businessman of Slovak origin
